metadata.name: Absorbed #198
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF‚Äôs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT‚Ñ¢). 

MAT‚Ñ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT‚Ñ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed ‚Äì high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and ‚Äúsinusoidal‚Äù noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists‚Äô belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica‚Äôs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: A Pile, To Be Sorted #86
metadata.description:
Compartmentalization in service of clarity.
Dedicated to my Dad and, by extension, his advice.

When I get overwhelmed (which is often), I typically call my dad. He‚Äôs always got some relatable story from his life I‚Äôve never heard before, OR he hits me with the same piece of advice he‚Äôs been giving me for as long as I can remember:

‚ÄúOf course it‚Äôs hard to stay calm when you look at the pile in front of you. Every responsibility, want and obligation, is not something we‚Äôre meant to face all at once. Break it up, take on one task from the pile, and focus on that.‚Äù

This has been such a stable pattern that I often don‚Äôt need to hear him say it. I‚Äôll finish describing what‚Äôs going on and stop him before he can even start, so he doesn‚Äôt have to waste his breath on something I should know by now, it‚Äôs already helping just to remember it.

The best thing I can do for myself is to pick something out of the pile and handle it in isolation. I find that often each task will grow the pile exponentially. It‚Äôs easy to handle my health and fitness when that‚Äôs all I have to think about. But then I have to think about finances, maintaining friendships, taking care of my plants, dating, and finding time for a hobby. Each one of those things has its own nuances and complications. With all that in mind, going to the gym sounds overwhelming.

But‚Äî Going to the gym is easy. Pick one thing, focus, get it done, and watch the pile shrink. Repeat.

I‚Äôve opted to create a design which illustrates this overwhelm and demonstrates how quickly those individual tasks lose form in the pile.

Press 's' to save a .png
Press '1', '2', or '3' to change render size
Press 't' to toggle linen texture (for use printing onto textured paper or cloth)

Created by Chris McCully in October 2023 using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL

metadata.name: Sansuhwa #30
metadata.description: Once upon a time, in a house in an oriental village, you can see beautiful nature when you look at the window. This painting of nature is called "Sansuhwa." You can see the sun or the moon, the mountains, the sea, and the forest, but sometimes you can only see a part of them. And what you see in the bottom right is the way that Asian painting usually signs paintings. Usually, it is written in Chinese characters, but I made it specially in Korean.

metadata.name: Chaotic cascade #77
metadata.description:
This project is an experiment with Clifford's attractors.

The title refers to the way in which the drawing reveals itself, but it can also be seen as an ecosystem, in which creatures can emerge between the different sprays of water.


To download a JPG, click on the canvas.


---

Features

- palette: 10 palettes taken from art-historical paintings

- attractor constant: 10 constants (4 decimal numbers) that configure the attractors

- domain: a dimension that controls the drawing area

- scale: a number that defines the scale of the Perlin noise (texture)

- format: two choices of format, portrait (1920x2400) or square (2140x2140)

--- 

Made with p5js 
Nicolas Lebrun @nclslbrn/nicolas-lebrun.fr

metadata.name: Topographic Playing Card #93
metadata.description:
Topographic Playing Card is an attempt to create a pseudo-japanese fantasy map.
Every line consists of randomly spaced lines to simulate the delicate strokes of a brush,
imitating grassy planes and the whitespace symoolizes a body of water.

The colors are randomly choosen from a fixed list of palettes.

Every card has a small chance of being animated. The card can be flipped to
reveal a CSS pattern serving as the card back and generally points towards your mouse cursor when interacting with it.

metadata.name: Shape Study  #86
metadata.description:
‚ÄúEveryone has their own shape.‚Äù
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone‚Äôs collection.

‚ÄúWhy do they need to have so many similar things?‚Äù

Perhaps it‚Äôs their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they‚Äôre meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what‚Äôs visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It‚Äôs only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: NAZCA #6
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

üëΩ Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: DOM II #177
metadata.description:
Owners of DOM will receive FREE AirDrop!

From Proto-Indo-European *d·πìm (‚Äúhouse, home‚Äù), from root *dem- (‚Äúto build‚Äù).

The humans use of stone in architecture and housing dates back to the dawn of civilisation, where its excellence in material, ecological and aesthetic qualities recalls the original concept of home, intended as a shelter from the external world.
The word Home is more representing of the true meaning of DOM as it is tied to the sense of family, homeland and provenance. The place where the heart is.

As a culmination of my personal generative art journey, the DOM II is a natural sequel and a closer, much deeper & intimate look to ancient cities/ villages architecture and typical stone houses. Inspired by Dalmatia coastal & Herzegovina hinterland but you will hopefully find your own dream home.

Thank You!
